Project 1 Data Analysis¶

The extent of analysis of a dataset is largely up to the analyst. There is much subjectivity when deciding how to explore a dataset. How much is too much exploration, to a point where you are not getting any information from some charts? What if you do not explore enough, will you miss key patterns and correlations between variables?

For Project 1 exploration, since we are relatively new to analyzing your data, I will give you exactly what I need from your analysis. If you do the minimum exploration I have listed here, then you will get a 87%-90% on this portion of the project. If you add more insightful analysis on your own, you will get an A.

import pandas as pd
csv_files = [
    'circuits.csv', 'constructor_results.csv', 'constructor_standings.csv',
    'constructors.csv', 'driver_standings.csv', 'drivers.csv', 'lap_times.csv',
    'pit_stops.csv', 'qualifying.csv', 'races.csv', 'results.csv', 'seasons.csv',
    'sprint_results.csv', 'status.csv'
]

    summary_statistics = data.describe(include='all')

    print("-" * 50)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd


circuits['alt'] = pd.to_numeric(circuits['alt'], errors='coerce')

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
sns.boxplot(y='alt', data=circuits)  
plt.title('Boxplot for Altitude of F1 Circuits')
plt.ylabel('Altitude (meters above sea level)')
plt.show()

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
sns.boxplot(y='grid', data=sprint_results)

plt.ylabel('Starting Grid Position')
plt.show()

import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

data_frames = {}
for name in data_frame_names:
    df = pd.read_csv(f'{name}.csv')
    data_frames[name] = df

for key, df in data_frames.items():
    numerical_variables = df.select_dtypes(include=['number'])
    data_frames[key] = numerical_variables

combined_df = pd.concat(data_frames.values(), axis=1)

correlation_matrix = combined_df.corr()

plt.figure(figsize=(50, 40))
sns.heatmap(correlation_matrix, annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', fmt=".2f")
plt.title('Correlation Matrix')
plt.show()

import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

csv_files = [
    'circuits.csv',
    'constructors.csv',
    'constructor_results.csv',
    'constructor_standings.csv',
    'drivers.csv',
    'driver_standings.csv',
    'lap_times.csv',
    'pit_stops.csv',
    'qualifying.csv',
    'races.csv',
    'results.csv',
    'seasons.csv',
    'sprint_results.csv',
    'status.csv'
]

def find_strong_correlations(df, threshold):
    correlation_matrix = df.corr()
    strongly_correlated_pairs = []

    for i in range(len(correlation_matrix.columns)):
        for j in range(i):
            if abs(correlation_matrix.iloc[i, j]) > threshold:
                strongly_correlated_pairs.append((correlation_matrix.columns[i], correlation_matrix.columns[j], correlation_matrix.iloc[i, j]))

    return strongly_correlated_pairs

threshold = 0.8

for csv_file in csv_files:
    df = pd.read_csv(csv_file)
    
    strongly_correlated_vars = find_strong_correlations(df, threshold)
    
    if strongly_correlated_vars:
        print(f'Strongly correlated variables in {csv_file}:')
        for var1, var2, correlation in strongly_correlated_vars:
            print(f'{var1} and {var2} (Correlation: {correlation:.2f})')
        print('\n')
